    fullDescription: "The Museu Nacional do Azulejo tells the story of the blue-and-white ceramic tiles that cover so much of Lisbon, and it's a quiet delight often overlooked by first-time visitors. Housed in the former Convento da Madre de Deus, founded in 1509, it walks you chronologically through five centuries of azulejo art, from geometric Hispano-Moorish patterns through exuberant Baroque narrative panels to Art Nouveau and bold contemporary pieces. The single most remarkable exhibit is a 23-metre panorama of Lisbon in around 1700, laid out in thousands of tiles, showing the waterfront city exactly as it was before the 1755 earthquake erased it. The building itself is half the reward: a serene Manueline cloister and, upstairs, the breathtaking convent church, its walls sheathed in blue tiles and dripping with gilded Baroque woodwork. There's a pretty tiled café-restaurant in a former kitchen too. It sits a little east of the centre, so pair it with a riverside walk, and give it around 90 minutes — it's inexpensive and consistently a highlight for anyone who lingers.",
